### Git & GitHub Questions & Answers

# What is Git?
Git is a distributed version control system that tracks changes in code and helps multiple people
work on the same project.

# What is GitHub?
GitHub is a cloud platform where Git repositories are stored and shared.

# What is a Repository?
A repository (repo) is a project folder tracked by Git. It can be local or remote.

# What is `git init`?
Creates a new Git repository.

# Difference: `git init` vs `git clone`
`git init` starts a new repo. `git clone` copies an existing repo from GitHub.

# What is Staging Area?
A temporary area where changes are prepared before commit.

# What is a Commit?
A snapshot of your code at a point in time.

# What is a Branch?
A separate workspace to develop features without affecting main code.

# Why do we use Branches?
To work safely, in parallel, and merge changes easily.

# What is Merging?
Combining one branch into another.

# What is a Merge Conflict?
When two people edit the same line, Git can’t decide which version to use.

# What is Push and Pull?
Push uploads changes to GitHub, Pull downloads latest changes.
Difference: `git pull` vs `git fetch`
`git pull` = fetch + merge, `git fetch` = only fetch.

# What is a Fork?
A personal copy of someone else's repo on GitHub.

# What is a Pull Request?
A request to merge your branch into another branch or repo.

# What is `.gitignore`?
A file that tells Git which files NOT to track.

# What is Git Stash?
Temporarily saves uncommitted changes.

# What is Git Tag?
Used to mark versions/releases.

# What is HEAD in Git?
Pointer to the latest commit in the current branch.

# What is Fast-Forward Merge?
A merge where no extra commit is created because history is linear.

# What is Rebase?
Rewrites commit history to make it linear.

Difference: Merge vs Rebase
Merge keeps full history. Rebase rewrites history to keep it clean.

# What is CI/CD role of GitHub?
Stores code that CI/CD tools use for build, test, deploy.

# What are GitHub Actions?
GitHub’s CI/CD automation service.

# What is SSH vs HTTPS in Git?
HTTPS uses login, SSH uses secure key-based login.